16
00:03:44,099 --> 00:03:48,477
But I want it to sound rich
and almost a little wavy...

17
00:03:48,687 --> 00:03:51,063
...due to being a bit out of tune.

18
00:03:51,273 --> 00:03:53,566
- You want it...
- Slightly detached.

19
00:03:53,817 --> 00:03:55,776
That's what I was wondering.

20
00:03:56,278 --> 00:03:57,278
We're going:

21
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:01,782
- Yeah. You got it.
- Okay.

22
00:04:02,117 --> 00:04:04,243
Snazzy, people!

23
00:04:04,453 --> 00:04:07,413
Okay, pickup to 20, please.

24
00:04:07,623 --> 00:04:09,665
- This is the pickup to 20.
- Okay.

25
00:04:09,875 --> 00:04:11,500
One, two, three.

26
00:05:09,393 --> 00:05:12,311
Hey, it's me.
I just got back into town.

27
00:05:12,521 --> 00:05:15,648
I thought I'd bum a ride,
but that's cool.

28
00:05:15,857 --> 00:05:19,527
I can just take a cab,
something like that.

29
00:05:22,114 --> 00:05:25,741
I guess I'll hang out with you later
or something.

30
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:40,589
Ahoy there, matey!
You in for the long haul?

31
00:05:40,966 --> 00:05:43,968
Do you need a lift on down the line?

32
00:05:44,386 --> 00:05:48,472
I was waiting for a cab, but...

33
00:05:48,682 --> 00:05:51,767
All right. Don't miss the boat.

34
00:05:53,353 --> 00:05:55,730
- Hey, thanks.
- Not a problem.

35
00:05:55,939 --> 00:05:58,399
Anchors aweigh!

36
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:04,655
What do you think of my vessel?

37
00:06:04,865 --> 00:06:08,492
She's "see-worthy." S-E-E.
See with your eyes.

38
00:06:08,702 --> 00:06:12,997
My transport should be an extension
of my personality. VoilÃ !

39
00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:18,044
And this is my window to the world.
Every minute's a different show.

40
00:06:18,253 --> 00:06:21,380
I may not understand it
or agree with it...

41
00:06:21,631 --> 00:06:25,217
...but I accept it
and just sort of glide along.

42
00:06:25,510 --> 00:06:28,054
Keep things on an even keel, I say.

43
00:06:28,263 --> 00:06:31,766
Go with the flow.
The sea refuses no river.

44
00:06:31,975 --> 00:06:37,063
The idea is to remain in a state
of departure, while always arriving.

45
00:06:37,314 --> 00:06:40,107
It saves on introductions
and goodbyes.

46
00:06:40,317 --> 00:06:43,569
The ride requires no explanation,
just occupants.

47
00:06:43,779 --> 00:06:45,696
That's where you come in.

48
00:06:45,906 --> 00:06:50,034
It's like you come onto this planet
with a crayon box.

49
00:06:50,243 --> 00:06:54,080
You may get the eight-pack
or the 16-pack...

50
00:06:54,289 --> 00:06:59,335
...but it's all in what you do with
the crayons, the colors you're given.

51
00:06:59,586 --> 00:07:02,755
Don't worry about coloring
within the lines.

52
00:07:02,964 --> 00:07:07,176
Color outside the lines
and off the page! Don't box me in!

53
00:07:07,427 --> 00:07:11,931
We're in motion to the ocean.
We are not landlocked!

54
00:07:12,140 --> 00:07:14,266
So where do you want out?

55
00:07:14,643 --> 00:07:19,146
Who, me? Am I first? I don't know.
Really, anywhere is fine.

56
00:07:19,564 --> 00:07:23,150
- Just give me an address, okay?
- Uh...

57
00:07:23,527 --> 00:07:26,445
Tell you what.
Go up three more streets.

58
00:07:26,655 --> 00:07:31,867
Take a right. Go two more blocks.
Drop him off on the next corner.

59
00:07:33,829 --> 00:07:34,995
Where's that?

60
00:07:35,664 --> 00:07:37,957
I don't know, but it's somewhere.

61
00:07:38,166 --> 00:07:42,461
And it'll determine the course
of the rest of your life.

62
00:07:43,255 --> 00:07:45,798
All ashore that's going ashore!

63
00:07:46,007 --> 00:07:47,049
Toot, toot.

64
00:09:15,138 --> 00:09:19,266
I refuse to take existentialism
as just another fashion...

65
00:09:19,476 --> 00:09:21,435
...or historical curiosity...

66
00:09:21,686 --> 00:09:26,565
...because it has something important
to offer for the new century.

67
00:09:27,025 --> 00:09:31,445
I'm afraid we're losing the real
virtues of living life passionately...

68
00:09:31,655 --> 00:09:34,698
...taking responsibility
for who you are...

69
00:09:34,908 --> 00:09:38,911
...making something of yourself
and feeling good about life.

70
00:09:39,287 --> 00:09:43,707
Existentialism is often discussed
as a philosophy of despair...

71
00:09:43,917 --> 00:09:46,126
...but I think it's the opposite.

72
00:09:46,378 --> 00:09:51,257
Sartre once said he never really
felt a day of despair in his life.

73
00:09:51,841 --> 00:09:54,551
One thing that comes
from these guys...

74
00:09:54,761 --> 00:09:58,180
...is not a sense of anguish
so much as...

75
00:09:58,390 --> 00:10:00,849
...an exuberance of feeling
on top of it.

76
00:10:01,101 --> 00:10:04,770
It's like your life
is yours to create.

77
00:10:05,021 --> 00:10:09,525
I've read
the postmodernists with interest.

78
00:10:10,402 --> 00:10:14,238
But I always have this awful,
nagging feeling...

79
00:10:14,447 --> 00:10:17,199
...that something essential
is left out.

80
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:20,744
The more you talk about a person...

81
00:10:21,037 --> 00:10:25,457
...as a social construction
or a confluence of forces...

82
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:28,752
...or as fragmented or marginalized...

83
00:10:28,962 --> 00:10:32,631
...then you open up
a whole new world of excuses.

84
00:10:32,841 --> 00:10:37,344
When Sartre talks about
responsibility, it's not abstract.

85
00:10:37,554 --> 00:10:41,849
It's not the kind of self or soul
that theologians argue about.

86
00:10:42,100 --> 00:10:45,352
It's something concrete.
It's us talking...

87
00:10:45,562 --> 00:10:49,231
...making decisions
and taking the consequences.

88
00:10:49,774 --> 00:10:53,152
There are six billion
people in the world.

89
00:10:53,570 --> 00:10:56,613
Nevertheless, what you do
makes a difference.

90
00:10:56,823 --> 00:11:01,618
It makes a difference
in material terms and to other people.

91
00:11:01,828 --> 00:11:03,787
It sets an example.

92
00:11:04,039 --> 00:11:07,875
The message is, we should
never write ourselves off...

93
00:11:08,084 --> 00:11:12,004
...and see ourselves as victims
of various forces.

94
00:11:12,255 --> 00:11:15,591
It's always our decision who we are.

95
00:11:25,101 --> 00:11:27,811
Creation comes out of imperfection.

96
00:11:28,021 --> 00:11:33,442
It seems to come out of a striving
and a frustration.

97
00:11:33,651 --> 00:11:36,737
This is where, I think,
language came from.

98
00:11:36,946 --> 00:11:42,326
I mean, it came from our desire
to transcend our isolation...

99
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:46,288
...and have some connection
with one another.

100
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:50,417
It had to be easy when
it was just simple survival.

101
00:11:50,668 --> 00:11:53,712
"Water." We came up
with a sound for that.

102
00:11:53,922 --> 00:11:57,049
"Tiger behind you!"
We made a sound for that.

103
00:11:57,300 --> 00:12:01,178
But when it gets really
interesting, I think...

104
00:12:01,388 --> 00:12:06,183
...is when we use
that same system of symbols...

105
00:12:06,476 --> 00:12:11,855
...to communicate all the abstract and
intangible things we're experiencing.

106
00:12:12,065 --> 00:12:17,027
What is "frustration"?
Or what is "anger" or "love"?

107
00:12:17,237 --> 00:12:19,613
When I say "love"...

108
00:12:19,864 --> 00:12:24,326
...the sound comes out of my mouth
and hits the other person's ear...

109
00:12:24,536 --> 00:12:28,956
...travels through this byzantine
conduit in their brain...

110
00:12:29,165 --> 00:12:33,085
...through their memories of love
or lack of love.

111
00:12:33,336 --> 00:12:39,258
They say they understand, but how
do I know? Because words are inert.

112
00:12:39,467 --> 00:12:42,803
They're just symbols. They're dead.
You know?

113
00:12:43,054 --> 00:12:47,516
And so much of our experience
is intangible.

114
00:12:47,725 --> 00:12:52,688
So much of what we perceive cannot
be expressed. It's unspeakable.

115
00:12:53,106 --> 00:12:57,609
And yet, you know, when we
communicate with one another...

116
00:12:59,988 --> 00:13:04,408
...and we feel we have connected
and think we're understood...

117
00:13:04,617 --> 00:13:09,329
...I think we have a feeling
of almost spiritual communion.

118
00:13:09,581 --> 00:13:13,625
That feeling may be transient,
but it's what we live for.

119
00:13:24,762 --> 00:13:28,849
To look at human development,
look at the organism's evolution...

120
00:13:29,058 --> 00:13:31,810
...and his environmental interaction.

121
00:13:32,020 --> 00:13:37,149
Evolution of the organism begins
with evolution through the hominid...

122
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:41,570
...coming to the evolution of man.
Neanderthal, Cro-Magnon.

123
00:13:41,779 --> 00:13:45,616
Now, what you're looking at here
are three strings:

124
00:13:45,825 --> 00:13:49,578
Biological, anthropological,
development of cultures...

125
00:13:49,829 --> 00:13:53,332
...and cultural,
which is human expression.

126
00:13:53,541 --> 00:13:58,128
What you've seen is the evolution
of populations, not individuals.

127
00:13:58,338 --> 00:14:01,131
Then look at the time scale involved.

128
00:14:01,341 --> 00:14:06,136
Two billion years for life,
six million for the hominid...

129
00:14:06,346 --> 00:14:09,515
...100,000 years for mankind
as we know it.

130
00:14:09,724 --> 00:14:12,726
You see how the evolutionary
paradigm telescopes.

131
00:14:12,936 --> 00:14:18,899
Then when you get to agriculture,
scientific and industrial revolution...

132
00:14:19,108 --> 00:14:22,778
...you're looking at 10,000 years,
400 years, 150 years.

133
00:14:23,029 --> 00:14:26,406
You see a further telescoping
of evolutionary time.

134
00:14:26,658 --> 00:14:29,284
As we go through the new evolution...

135
00:14:29,494 --> 00:14:35,499
...it will telescope to the point
where we see it within our lifetime.

136
00:14:35,750 --> 00:14:39,878
The new evolution stems
from two types of information:

137
00:14:40,088 --> 00:14:43,507
Digital and analog.
Digital is artificial intelligence.

138
00:14:43,758 --> 00:14:47,177
Analog results from molecular biology
and cloning.

139
00:14:47,387 --> 00:14:49,846
You knit the two with neurobiology.

140
00:14:50,098 --> 00:14:54,768
Under the old paradigm, one would
die, the other would dominate.

141
00:14:54,978 --> 00:14:58,981
Under the new paradigm, they exist
as a supportive...

142
00:14:59,190 --> 00:15:03,443
...non-competitive grouping,
independent from the external.

143
00:15:03,695 --> 00:15:07,906
So evolution now becomes an
individually centered process...

144
00:15:08,283 --> 00:15:11,076
...emanating from the individual...

145
00:15:11,244 --> 00:15:16,456
...not a passive process with the
individual at the collective's whim.

146
00:15:16,749 --> 00:15:19,459
So you produce a neo-human...

147
00:15:19,669 --> 00:15:22,838
...with a new individuality,
a new consciousness.

148
00:15:23,047 --> 00:15:26,174
That's only the beginning
of the cycle.

149
00:15:26,384 --> 00:15:30,137
As it proceeds,
the input is this new intelligence.

150
00:15:30,346 --> 00:15:34,266
As intelligence piles on intelligence,
ability on ability...

151
00:15:34,475 --> 00:15:37,644
...the speed changes until you reach
a crescendo.

152
00:15:37,854 --> 00:15:43,900
Imagine it as an instant fulfillment
of human and neo-human potential.

153
00:15:44,110 --> 00:15:47,696
It could be the amplification
of the individual...

154
00:15:47,905 --> 00:15:51,742
...the multiplication of individual,
parallel existences...

155
00:15:51,909 --> 00:15:56,204
...with the individual no longer
restricted by time and space.

156
00:15:56,414 --> 00:16:00,500
And the manifestations of this
neo-human evolution...

157
00:16:00,710 --> 00:16:03,879
...could be dramatically
counterintuitive.

158
00:16:04,088 --> 00:16:08,550
The old evolution is cold,
it's sterile. It's efficient.

159
00:16:08,760 --> 00:16:11,720
Its manifestations are
those of social adaption.

160
00:16:11,971 --> 00:16:16,600
You're talking about parasitism,
dominance, morality...

161
00:16:16,851 --> 00:16:18,435
...war, predation.

162
00:16:18,686 --> 00:16:22,898
These will be subject to de-emphasis
and de-evolution.

163
00:16:23,107 --> 00:16:26,610
The new paradigm would give us
the traits...

164
00:16:26,861 --> 00:16:30,864
...of truth, loyalty,
justice and freedom.

165
00:16:31,115 --> 00:16:36,536
These would be manifestations of
this evolution. That's what we hope.

166
00:18:26,355 --> 00:18:31,693
Self-destructive man feels completely
alienated. Utterly alone.

167
00:18:31,903 --> 00:18:34,362
He's an outsider to the community.

168
00:18:34,572 --> 00:18:37,866
He thinks to himself,
"I must be insane."

169
00:18:38,117 --> 00:18:42,162
What he fails to realize
is that society has, as he does...

170
00:18:42,413 --> 00:18:46,458
...an interest in considerable
losses, in catastrophes.

171
00:18:46,667 --> 00:18:50,879
Wars, famines, floods and quakes
meet well-defined needs.

172
00:18:55,426 --> 00:18:59,387
Man wants chaos.
In fact, he's gotta have it.

173
00:18:59,597 --> 00:19:04,226
Depression, strife, riots, murder.
All this dread.

174
00:19:04,435 --> 00:19:10,106
We're drawn to that almost orgiastic
state created out of destruction.

175
00:19:10,316 --> 00:19:13,568
It's in all of us. We revel in it.

176
00:19:15,613 --> 00:19:20,742
The media puts a sad face on things,
painting them as human tragedies.

177
00:19:21,077 --> 00:19:26,289
But the media's function is not
to eliminate the evils of the world.

178
00:19:26,499 --> 00:19:31,461
They persuade us to accept those evils
and get used to living with them.

179
00:19:31,671 --> 00:19:35,423
The powers that be
want us to be passive observers.

180
00:19:36,050 --> 00:19:38,134
Have you got a match?

181
00:19:39,887 --> 00:19:44,099
They haven't given us any other
options, outside the occasional...

182
00:19:44,308 --> 00:19:48,395
...purely symbolic,
participatory act of "voting."

183
00:19:48,604 --> 00:19:53,316
Do you want the puppet on the right
or the puppet on the left?

184
00:19:53,568 --> 00:19:58,071
The time has come to project my
inadequacies and dissatisfactions...

185
00:19:58,322 --> 00:20:02,242
...into the sociopolitical
and scientific schemes.

186
00:20:02,493 --> 00:20:05,996
Let my own lack of a voice be heard.

187
00:21:10,811 --> 00:21:13,355
I keep thinking about
something you said.

188
00:21:13,606 --> 00:21:15,815
- Something I said?
- Yeah.

189
00:21:16,150 --> 00:21:19,152
About feeling like you
observe your life...

190
00:21:19,320 --> 00:21:23,490
...from the perspective of
an old woman about to die. Remember?

191
00:21:23,658 --> 00:21:27,077
Yeah. I still feel that way sometimes.

192
00:21:27,328 --> 00:21:29,704
Like I'm looking back on my life.

193
00:21:29,956 --> 00:21:32,499
Like my waking life is her memories.

194
00:21:32,708 --> 00:21:34,668
Exactly.

195
00:21:35,670 --> 00:21:39,506
I heard that Tim Leary said
as he was dying...

196
00:21:39,715 --> 00:21:44,135
...he looked forward to when his
body was dead but his brain was alive.

197
00:21:44,345 --> 00:21:49,766
Those six to 12 minutes of brain
activity after everything shuts down.

198
00:21:49,976 --> 00:21:55,814
And a second of dream consciousness
is infinitely longer than a waking one.

199
00:21:56,065 --> 00:21:57,607
- Know what I mean?
- Yeah.

200
00:21:58,025 --> 00:22:01,528
Like, I wake up at 10:12.
Then I go back to sleep...

201
00:22:01,779 --> 00:22:07,367
...and have long, intricate dreams that
seem hours long. Then I wake up and...

202
00:22:07,535 --> 00:22:08,618
...it's 10:13.

203
00:22:08,869 --> 00:22:14,082
Exactly. So in that six to 12 minutes
of brain activity...

204
00:22:14,291 --> 00:22:16,126
...that could be your life.

205
00:22:16,335 --> 00:22:20,755
You are that woman,
looking back over everything.

206
00:22:20,965 --> 00:22:23,800
If I am? What would you be in that?

207
00:22:23,968 --> 00:22:25,468
Whatever I am now.

208
00:22:25,678 --> 00:22:29,014
I mean, maybe I only exist
in your mind.

209
00:22:29,181 --> 00:22:32,892
I'm still just as real
as anything else.

210
00:22:33,936 --> 00:22:35,311
Yeah.

211
00:22:36,022 --> 00:22:38,565
I've been thinking about
something you said.

212
00:22:38,733 --> 00:22:39,733
What's that?

213
00:22:39,942 --> 00:22:44,904
About reincarnation, and where
all the new souls come from over time.

214
00:22:45,364 --> 00:22:46,865
Everybody always...

215
00:22:47,116 --> 00:22:52,579
...says they're the reincarnation
of Cleopatra or Alexander the Great.

216
00:22:52,788 --> 00:22:55,915
You know they were a dumb fuck
like everyone else.

217
00:22:56,125 --> 00:22:58,001
I mean, it's impossible.

218
00:22:58,252 --> 00:23:02,922
The world population has doubled
in the past 40 years.

219
00:23:03,132 --> 00:23:08,011
- So if you believe in one eternal soul...
- Uh-huh.

220
00:23:08,345 --> 00:23:11,931
...you have a 50% chance of your soul
being over 40.

221
00:23:12,224 --> 00:23:17,729
For it to be over 150 years old,
it's only one out of six.

222
00:23:17,938 --> 00:23:23,068
Are you saying reincarnation doesn't
exist? Or we're all young souls?

223
00:23:23,277 --> 00:23:27,030
- Half of us are first-round humans?
- No, no.

224
00:23:27,239 --> 00:23:29,657
- What I'm saying...
- What's your point?

225
00:23:29,950 --> 00:23:34,412
I believe reincarnation
is a poetic expression...

226
00:23:34,622 --> 00:23:36,831
...of what collective memory is.

227
00:23:37,041 --> 00:23:41,127
- I read an article by a biochemist.
- Right.

228
00:23:41,378 --> 00:23:44,756
He said when a member
of a species is born...

229
00:23:44,965 --> 00:23:48,718
...it has a billion years
of memory to draw on.

230
00:23:49,053 --> 00:23:52,555
This is where we inherit
our instincts.

231
00:23:52,848 --> 00:23:55,141
I like that. Like there's...

232
00:23:55,351 --> 00:23:59,270
...this telepathic thing going on
that we're a part of...

233
00:23:59,522 --> 00:24:04,234
...whether we're conscious of it
or not. That would explain these...

