01:00:26,790 --> 01:00:30,167
Demonstrate what life is
and what it could be.

695
01:00:30,377 --> 01:00:33,713
To immerse ourselves
in the oblivion of actions.

696
01:00:33,922 --> 01:00:38,134
There'll be an intensity never known.
To exchange love and hate...

697
01:00:38,343 --> 01:00:40,636
...terror and redemption.

698
01:00:40,887 --> 01:00:47,143
Affirmation of freedom so reckless
it amounts to a denial of limitation.

699
01:00:58,363 --> 01:01:01,532
- Hey, what are you doing?
- I'm not sure.

700
01:01:02,159 --> 01:01:04,994
You need any help getting down, sir?

701
01:01:05,954 --> 01:01:08,622
No, I don't think so.

702
01:01:09,541 --> 01:01:11,584
Stupid bastard.

703
01:01:11,793 --> 01:01:14,879
No worse than us.
He's all action, no theory.

704
01:01:15,589 --> 01:01:18,257
We're all theory and no action.

705
01:01:27,559 --> 01:01:29,643
Why so glum, Mr. Deborg?

706
01:01:29,853 --> 01:01:34,398
What was missing
was felt irretrievable.

707
01:01:34,941 --> 01:01:40,863
The extreme uncertainties
of subsisting without working...

708
01:01:41,073 --> 01:01:44,075
...made excesses necessary...

709
01:01:44,284 --> 01:01:46,410
...and breaks definitive.

710
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:48,454
To quote Stevenson:

711
01:01:48,663 --> 01:01:52,416
"Suicide carried off many.

712
01:01:52,751 --> 01:01:56,087
Drink and the devil...

713
01:01:56,296 --> 01:01:58,839
...took care of the rest."

714
01:02:09,101 --> 01:02:10,726
- Hey!
- Hey.

715
01:02:11,770 --> 01:02:13,771
Are you a dreamer?

716
01:02:15,148 --> 01:02:16,690
Yeah.

717
01:02:19,027 --> 01:02:22,363
I haven't seen too many around lately.

718
01:02:22,697 --> 01:02:25,324
Things have been tough for dreamers.

719
01:02:26,201 --> 01:02:29,495
They say dreaming's dead.
No one does it anymore.

720
01:02:30,080 --> 01:02:32,832
It's not dead.
It's just been forgotten.

721
01:02:33,291 --> 01:02:35,084
Removed from our language.

722
01:02:35,293 --> 01:02:38,796
Nobody teaches it,
so no one knows it exists.

723
01:02:41,133 --> 01:02:44,093
The dreamer's banished to obscurity.

724
01:02:44,803 --> 01:02:48,139
I'm trying to change that.
I hope you are too...

725
01:02:49,266 --> 01:02:51,809
...by dreaming every day.

726
01:02:53,186 --> 01:02:55,729
Dreaming with our hands and minds.

727
01:02:56,398 --> 01:03:01,026
Our planet is facing the greatest
problems it's ever faced. Ever.

728
01:03:01,236 --> 01:03:03,070
So don't be bored.

729
01:03:03,280 --> 01:03:07,658
This is the most exciting time
we could have hoped to be alive.

730
01:03:07,909 --> 01:03:10,286
And things are just starting.

731
01:03:26,511 --> 01:03:30,264
A thousand years is
an instant. There's nothing new.

732
01:03:30,515 --> 01:03:36,228
The same pattern over and over.
The same insights felt long ago.

733
01:03:36,438 --> 01:03:39,231
There's nothing here for me now.

734
01:03:39,441 --> 01:03:44,737
Now I remember. This happened
to me before. This is why I left.

735
01:03:46,490 --> 01:03:48,532
You have begun to find answers.

736
01:03:48,742 --> 01:03:51,494
Though difficult,
the rewards will be great.

737
01:03:51,745 --> 01:03:56,457
Exercise your mind fully,
knowing it is only an exercise.

738
01:03:56,708 --> 01:04:01,504
Build artifacts, solve problems,
explore the secrets of the universe.

739
01:04:01,713 --> 01:04:04,089
Savor input from all the senses.

740
01:04:04,341 --> 01:04:10,262
Feel joy, sorrow, laughter, empathy.
Tuck the memory in your travel bag.

741
01:04:10,597 --> 01:04:13,933
I remember where I'm from
and how I became human.

742
01:04:14,142 --> 01:04:17,394
Why I hung around.
Now my departure is scheduled.

743
01:04:17,938 --> 01:04:23,150
This way out. Escaping velocity.
Not just eternity, but infinity.

744
01:04:50,220 --> 01:04:52,846
- Excuse me.
- Excuse me.

745
01:04:56,893 --> 01:04:58,602
Hey.

746
01:04:58,770 --> 01:05:02,106
Could we do that again?
I know we haven't met...

747
01:05:02,357 --> 01:05:04,858
...but I don't want to be an ant.

748
01:05:05,902 --> 01:05:09,446
We go through life
bouncing off one another...

749
01:05:09,656 --> 01:05:12,408
...continuously on ant autopilot...

750
01:05:12,617 --> 01:05:16,537
...with nothing really human
required of us.

751
01:05:16,830 --> 01:05:19,915
Stop. Go. Walk here. Drive there.

752
01:05:20,125 --> 01:05:22,585
All action basically for survival.

753
01:05:22,794 --> 01:05:26,714
All communication to keep
the ant colony buzzing along...

754
01:05:26,965 --> 01:05:29,425
...in an efficient, polite manner.

755
01:05:29,676 --> 01:05:34,388
"Here's your change."
"Paper or plastic?" "Credit or debit?"

756
01:05:34,598 --> 01:05:36,557
"Want ketchup with that?"

757
01:05:36,766 --> 01:05:40,894
I don't want a straw,
I want real human moments.

758
01:05:41,146 --> 01:05:44,398
I want to see you.
I want you to see me.

759
01:05:44,608 --> 01:05:48,986
I don't want to give that up.
I don't want to be an ant, you know?

760
01:05:50,030 --> 01:05:52,323
Yeah, no...

761
01:05:52,616 --> 01:05:55,326
...I don't want to be an ant, either.

762
01:05:55,702 --> 01:05:59,204
Thanks for kind ofjostling me there.
I've been...

763
01:05:59,456 --> 01:06:05,294
...on zombie autopilot. I don't feel
like an ant, but I look like one.

764
01:06:06,296 --> 01:06:10,049
D.H. Lawrence had this idea
of two people meeting...

765
01:06:10,300 --> 01:06:12,593
...and instead ofjust passing...

766
01:06:12,802 --> 01:06:16,805
...they accept "the confrontation
between their souls."

767
01:06:17,474 --> 01:06:21,602
It's like freeing the brave,
reckless gods within us all.

768
01:06:21,811 --> 01:06:24,355
Then it's like we have met.

769
01:06:25,148 --> 01:06:29,693
I'm doing a
soap opera, you might be interested.

770
01:06:29,986 --> 01:06:36,241
The characters are the fantasy
lives of the performers in it.

771
01:06:36,451 --> 01:06:41,914
So figure out something you've always
wanted to do, or a life you want...

772
01:06:42,123 --> 01:06:45,042
...something like that.
We write that in...

773
01:06:45,251 --> 01:06:51,757
...then you intersect with others
in some typical soap-opera fashion.

774
01:06:51,966 --> 01:06:56,762
Then I also want to show it live,
with the actors present.

775
01:06:57,013 --> 01:06:59,848
So once the episode's screened...

776
01:07:00,058 --> 01:07:06,146
...the audience can direct the actors
for subsequent episodes with menus.

777
01:07:06,439 --> 01:07:08,107
It has to do with choices...

778
01:07:08,316 --> 01:07:13,112
...and honoring people's ability
to say what it is they want to see...

779
01:07:13,363 --> 01:07:17,032
...and consumerism and art
and commodity...

780
01:07:17,242 --> 01:07:22,579
...and if you don't like it, send it
back, and you get what you pay for...

781
01:07:22,789 --> 01:07:26,542
...or just participating, you know,
making choices.

782
01:07:26,751 --> 01:07:28,877
So do you want to do it?

783
01:07:29,087 --> 01:07:34,216
Yeah, that sounds really cool.
I'd love to be in it, but...

784
01:07:35,427 --> 01:07:40,723
...I gotta ask you a question first.
I don't know how to say it, but...

785
01:07:41,683 --> 01:07:45,519
What's it like to be a character
in a dream? Because...

786
01:07:45,729 --> 01:07:50,357
...I'm not awake right now. I haven't
worn a watch since 4th grade.

787
01:07:50,567 --> 01:07:53,777
I think this is the same watch too.

788
01:07:55,280 --> 01:07:58,699
I don't know if you're able
to answer that question.

789
01:07:58,950 --> 01:08:04,163
I'm just trying to get a sense
of where I am and what's going on.

790
01:08:04,372 --> 01:08:07,040
What about you? What's your name?

791
01:08:07,250 --> 01:08:11,003
What's your address?
What are you doing?

792
01:08:13,006 --> 01:08:17,718
I can't really remember right now.
I can't really recall.

793
01:08:17,927 --> 01:08:23,432
But that's beside the point, whether
I can dredge up information about...

794
01:08:23,683 --> 01:08:29,021
...my address, or my mom's
maiden name or whatnot.

795
01:08:29,230 --> 01:08:33,650
I've got the benefit in this reality,
if you call it that...

796
01:08:33,860 --> 01:08:36,153
...of a consistent perspective.

797
01:08:36,404 --> 01:08:38,947
What is your consistent perspective?

798
01:08:39,199 --> 01:08:42,868
It's mostly just me
dealing with a lot of people...

799
01:08:43,119 --> 01:08:49,374
...who are exposing me
to information and ideas...

800
01:08:49,626 --> 01:08:52,294
...that seem vaguely familiar.

801
01:08:52,504 --> 01:08:56,715
But at the same time,
it's all very alien to me.

802
01:08:56,925 --> 01:09:01,512
I'm not in an objective,
rational world.

803
01:09:01,721 --> 01:09:05,224
Like, I've been flying around...

804
01:09:06,768 --> 01:09:09,728
It's weird,
because it's not a fixed state.

805
01:09:09,896 --> 01:09:13,357
It's more like a whole spectrum
of awareness.

806
01:09:13,650 --> 01:09:16,985
The lucidity wavers.
Right now I know I'm dreaming.

807
01:09:17,195 --> 01:09:19,988
We're even talking about it. This is...

808
01:09:20,198 --> 01:09:24,451
...the most in myself
and in my thoughts I've been so far.

809
01:09:24,661 --> 01:09:28,163
I'm talking about being in a dream.

810
01:09:28,373 --> 01:09:31,458
But I'm beginning to think...

811
01:09:31,668 --> 01:09:35,170
...it's something I don't have
any precedent for.

812
01:09:35,380 --> 01:09:38,048
It's totally unique.

813
01:09:38,258 --> 01:09:41,844
The quality of the environment...

814
01:09:42,053 --> 01:09:47,099
...and the information I'm receiving.
Like your soap opera, for example.

815
01:09:47,350 --> 01:09:50,018
That's a really cool idea!

816
01:09:50,228 --> 01:09:53,480
I didn't come up with that.
It's outside myself...

817
01:09:53,690 --> 01:09:57,484
...like something transmitted
to me externally.

818
01:09:57,735 --> 01:09:59,778
I don't know what this is.

819
01:09:59,946 --> 01:10:04,616
We think we're so limited
by the world and the confines...

820
01:10:04,826 --> 01:10:07,244
...but we're really
just creating them.

821
01:10:07,537 --> 01:10:13,375
You keep trying to figure it out,
but now you know you're dreaming...

822
01:10:13,585 --> 01:10:18,130
...you can do anything.
You're dreaming, but you're awake.

823
01:10:18,339 --> 01:10:20,257
You have...

824
01:10:20,633 --> 01:10:24,678
...so many options,
and that's what life is about.

825
01:10:24,888 --> 01:10:29,433
I understand what you're saying.
It's up to me, I'm the dreamer.

826
01:10:29,684 --> 01:10:30,934
It's weird.

827
01:10:31,144 --> 01:10:33,186
So much of the information...

828
01:10:33,396 --> 01:10:36,064
...these people have been imparting...

829
01:10:36,274 --> 01:10:40,027
...has got this
really heavy connotation to it.

830
01:10:40,612 --> 01:10:42,905
Well, how do you feel?

831
01:10:43,615 --> 01:10:46,450
Sometimes I feel kind of isolated.

832
01:10:46,659 --> 01:10:51,622
Most of the time, I feel connected,
engaged in this active process.

833
01:10:51,831 --> 01:10:57,544
Which is weird. Most of the time
I've been passive, not responding...

834
01:10:57,795 --> 01:10:59,212
...except for now.

835
01:10:59,380 --> 01:11:02,090
I've let information wash over me.

836
01:11:02,300 --> 01:11:06,511
It's not necessarily passive
to not respond verbally.

837
01:11:06,679 --> 01:11:11,892
We're communicating
on so many levels simultaneously.

838
01:11:12,143 --> 01:11:15,395
Perhaps you're perceiving directly.

839
01:11:16,022 --> 01:11:21,443
Most of the people I've encountered
and the things I want to say...

840
01:11:21,653 --> 01:11:25,447
...it's like they say it for me,
almost at my cue.

841
01:11:25,740 --> 01:11:29,785
It's complete unto itself.

842
01:11:30,536 --> 01:11:33,622
It's not a bad dream.
It's a great dream.

843
01:11:33,790 --> 01:11:35,415
But...

844
01:11:35,625 --> 01:11:40,253
...it's so unlike any other dream
I've ever had before.

845
01:11:40,505 --> 01:11:43,548
It's like "the" dream.

846
01:11:44,592 --> 01:11:47,052
It's like I'm being prepared
for something.

847
01:12:16,499 --> 01:12:20,085
"On this bridge," Lorca warns...

848
01:12:20,336 --> 01:12:22,379
..."life is not a dream.

849
01:12:22,588 --> 01:12:24,423
Beware and...

850
01:12:24,632 --> 01:12:28,635
...beware and beware."

851
01:12:28,845 --> 01:12:34,141
So many think because "then"
happened, "now" isn't.

852
01:12:34,350 --> 01:12:39,771
But didn't I mention? The ongoing
"wow" is happening right now.

853
01:12:39,981 --> 01:12:43,233
We are all coauthors
of this dancing exuberance...

854
01:12:43,484 --> 01:12:46,528
...where even our inabilities
are having a roast.

855
01:12:46,738 --> 01:12:51,324
We are the authors of ourselves,
coauthoring a Dostoyevsky novel...

856
01:12:51,534 --> 01:12:53,326
...starring clowns.

857
01:12:53,536 --> 01:12:56,079
This thing we're involved with,
the world...

858
01:12:56,330 --> 01:13:00,959
...is an opportunity to exhibit
how exciting alienation can be.

859
01:13:01,169 --> 01:13:03,920
Life is a matter of a miracle...

860
01:13:04,130 --> 01:13:09,176
...collected by moments flabbergasted
to be in each other's presence.

861
01:13:09,427 --> 01:13:10,969
The world is an exam...

862
01:13:11,220 --> 01:13:14,890
...to see if we can rise
into the direct experiences.

863
01:13:15,099 --> 01:13:18,685
Eyesight is a test
to see if we can see beyond it.

864
01:13:18,895 --> 01:13:21,813
Matter is a test for our curiosity.

865
01:13:22,023 --> 01:13:25,108
Doubt is an exam for our vitality.

866
01:13:25,485 --> 01:13:31,156
Thomas Mann wrote that he would rather
participate in life than write.

867
01:13:31,407 --> 01:13:35,535
Giacometti was once run down by a car.

868
01:13:35,745 --> 01:13:38,914
He recalled falling
into a lucid faint...

869
01:13:39,207 --> 01:13:40,957
...a sudden exhilaration...

870
01:13:41,209 --> 01:13:44,795
...as he realized
something was happening to him.

871
01:13:45,129 --> 01:13:49,883
One assumes you can't understand
life and live simultaneously.

872
01:13:50,093 --> 01:13:54,638
I don't agree entirely. Which is
to say, I don't exactly disagree.

873
01:13:55,014 --> 01:13:59,726
I would say that life understood
is life lived.

874
01:14:00,019 --> 01:14:02,312
But the paradoxes bug me.

875
01:14:02,522 --> 01:14:07,150
I can learn to love, and make love,
to the paradoxes that bug me.

876
01:14:07,360 --> 01:14:09,820
And on romantic evenings of self...

877
01:14:10,071 --> 01:14:13,115
...I go salsa dancing
with my confusion.

878
01:14:13,324 --> 01:14:16,535
Before you drift off, don't forget...

879
01:14:16,786 --> 01:14:18,537
...which is to say, remember.

880
01:14:18,788 --> 01:14:23,834
Because remembering is so much more
a psychotic activity than forgetting.

881
01:14:24,085 --> 01:14:26,545
Lorca, in that same poem, said...

882
01:14:26,754 --> 01:14:31,049
...that the iguana will bite
those who do not dream.

883
01:14:32,093 --> 01:14:35,220
And, as one realizes...

884
01:14:35,471 --> 01:14:40,851
...that one is a dream figure
in another person's dream...

885
01:14:41,477 --> 01:14:45,021
...that is self-awareness.

886
01:15:09,589 --> 01:15:12,591
You haven't met yourself yet.

887
01:15:14,218 --> 01:15:18,430
But the advantage to meeting others
in the meantime...

888
01:15:18,639 --> 01:15:23,268
...is that one of them
may present you to yourself.

889
01:15:25,229 --> 01:15:30,025
Examine the nature of everything
you observe.

890
01:15:30,276 --> 01:15:33,528
For instance,
you might find yourself...

891
01:15:33,779 --> 01:15:38,116
...walking through
a dream parking lot.

892
01:15:38,326 --> 01:15:42,370
And, yes, those are dream feet
inside your dream shoes.

893
01:15:42,663 --> 01:15:44,581
Part of your dream self.

894
01:15:44,790 --> 01:15:48,460
And so, the person you appear to be
in the dream...

895
01:15:48,669 --> 01:15:51,463
...cannot be who you really are.

896
01:15:51,672 --> 01:15:53,673
This is an image...

897
01:15:53,883 --> 01:15:56,509
...a mental model.

898
01:16:17,740 --> 01:16:22,285
- Do you remember me?
- No, I don't think so.

899
01:16:22,787 --> 01:16:27,749
At the station? You were on the
pay phone and you looked at me...

900
01:16:27,959 --> 01:16:29,918
...a few times.

901
01:16:30,920 --> 01:16:34,256
I remember that,
but I don't remember that being you.

902
01:16:35,132 --> 01:16:37,092
Are you sure?

903
01:16:39,470 --> 01:16:41,680
Maybe not.

904
01:16:41,973 --> 01:16:44,182
I was sitting down...

905
01:16:44,392 --> 01:16:47,394
...and you were looking at me.

906
01:17:41,657 --> 01:17:45,827
My little friend,
dream no more. It's really here.

907
01:17:46,037 --> 01:17:48,330
It's called Efferdent Plus.

908
01:17:48,539 --> 01:17:53,752
In hell, you sink. In heaven, you rise
to your fullness of love.

909
01:17:54,920 --> 01:17:58,548
Hurry up! Come on,
get in the car. Let's go.

910
01:17:59,050 --> 01:18:03,261
The story goes like this:
Billy Wilder runs into Louis Malle.

911
01:18:03,471 --> 01:18:05,764
This was the late '50s, early '60s.

912
01:18:06,015 --> 01:18:10,643
Malle had just made his most expensive
film, which cost $ 21/2 million.

913
01:18:10,895 --> 01:18:13,605
Wilder asks him what the film's about.

914
01:18:13,814 --> 01:18:16,649
Malle says, "It's a dream
within a dream."

915
01:18:16,859 --> 01:18:20,028
Wilder says,
"You just lost $ 21/2 million."

916
01:18:21,197 --> 01:18:23,740
I feel a little apprehensive.

917
01:18:31,082 --> 01:18:34,000
For years, the notion
that life is a dream...

918
01:18:34,251 --> 01:18:38,380
...has been a pervasive theme
of philosophers and poets.

919
01:18:38,589 --> 01:18:42,717
Doesn't it make sense that death
would be wrapped in a dream?

920
01:18:42,927 --> 01:18:48,932
That, after death, your conscious life
would continue in a dream body?

921
01:18:49,141 --> 01:18:53,520
It would be the same dream body
as in your everyday dream life...

922
01:18:53,771 --> 01:18:58,983
...except that in the post-mortal
state, you could never again wake up.

923
01:18:59,193 --> 01:19:02,237
Never again return
to your physical body.

924
01:19:12,790 --> 01:19:18,586
As the pattern gets more intricate,
being swept along isn't enough.

925
01:19:41,318 --> 01:19:43,027
What's the word, turd?

926
01:19:44,488 --> 01:19:48,658
- Hey, do you also drive a boat-car?
- A what?

927
01:19:49,076 --> 01:19:52,662
You gave me a ride in a car
that was also a boat.

928
01:19:52,872 --> 01:19:57,417
No, I don't have a "boat-car."
I don't know what you mean.

929
01:19:57,626 --> 01:20:03,256
This must be parallel universe night.
That cat who just ran out the door?

930
01:20:03,507 --> 01:20:06,050
He comes up and I say,
"What's the word?"

931
01:20:06,302 --> 01:20:10,054
He lays down a burrito,
looks at me and says:

932
01:20:10,264 --> 01:20:13,057
"I've returned
from the valley of death.

933
01:20:13,267 --> 01:20:16,311
I rapturously breathe in
the odors of life.

934
01:20:16,520 --> 01:20:22,609
I've been to oblivion. I ferment
the desire to remember everything."

935
01:20:24,820 --> 01:20:26,863
So, what did you say to that?

936
01:20:27,364 --> 01:20:29,574
Well, I mean, what could I say?

937
01:20:29,825 --> 01:20:33,495
I said, "If you microwave that,
poke holes in the plastic...

938
01:20:33,787 --> 01:20:38,917
...because they explode,
and I'm tired of cleaning up burrito."

939
01:20:43,964 --> 01:20:45,882
The jalapeÃ±os dry up.

940
01:20:46,759 --> 01:20:49,052
They're like little wheels.

941
01:20:52,681 --> 01:20:56,017
When it was over,
all I could think about was how...

942
01:20:56,227 --> 01:20:59,812
...this entire notion of oneself...

943
01:20:59,980 --> 01:21:01,022
...what we are...

944
01:21:01,273 --> 01:21:05,026
...is just this logical structure.

945
01:21:05,277 --> 01:21:10,323
A place to momentarily house
all the abstractions.

946
01:21:10,783 --> 01:21:13,409
It was a time to become conscious...

947
01:21:13,619 --> 01:21:17,872
...to give form and coherence
to the mystery.

948
01:21:18,082 --> 01:21:21,501
And I had been a part of that.
It was a gift.

949
01:21:22,753 --> 01:21:28,091
Life was raging all around me,
and every moment was magical.

950
01:21:28,676 --> 01:21:34,931
I loved all the people, dealing with
all the contradictory impulses.

951
01:21:35,140 --> 01:21:39,936
That's what I loved the most,
connecting with the people.

952
01:21:40,479 --> 01:21:43,898
Looking back, that's all
that really mattered.

953
01:22:41,248 --> 01:22:45,877
Kierkegaard's last words were,
"Sweep me up."

954
01:25:42,137 --> 01:25:43,888
- Hey, man.
- Hey.

955
01:25:50,854 --> 01:25:56,108
Weren't you in the boat-car?
The guy with the hat gave me a ride...

956
01:25:56,360 --> 01:26:00,112
...in his car-boat thing.
You were in the back seat.

957
01:26:00,364 --> 01:26:04,033
I'm not saying you don't know
what you're talking about...

958
01:26:04,243 --> 01:26:06,702
...but I don't know
what you're talking about.

959
01:26:06,995 --> 01:26:12,291
You guys let me off at this specific
spot you gave him directions to.

960
01:26:12,501 --> 01:26:15,044
I get out,
ended up getting hit by a car.

961
01:26:15,254 --> 01:26:17,463
Then I woke up. I was dreaming.

962
01:26:17,673 --> 01:26:23,219
Later I found out I was still
dreaming, dreaming that I'd woken up.

963
01:26:23,470 --> 01:26:26,639
False awakenings,
I used to have those a lot.

964
01:26:26,890 --> 01:26:30,393
But I'm still in it now.
I can't get out of it.

965
01:26:30,602 --> 01:26:35,731
It's been going on forever.
I keep waking up into another dream.

966
01:26:35,941 --> 01:26:39,902
I'm getting creeped out, like
I'm talking to dead people.

967
01:26:40,153 --> 01:26:43,406
This woman on TV tells me how death...

968
01:26:43,657 --> 01:26:47,577
...is this dream-time
that exists out of life.

969
01:26:48,829 --> 01:26:51,497
I'm starting to think I'm dead.

970
01:26:53,917 --> 01:26:56,210
Let me tell you about a dream I had.

971
01:26:56,420 --> 01:27:01,716
When someone says that, usually
you're in for a very boring few minutes.

972
01:27:02,009 --> 01:27:04,468
But what else are you gonna do?

973
01:27:04,720 --> 01:27:09,849
- I read this essay by Philip K. Dick.
- In your dream?

974
01:27:10,058 --> 01:27:13,895
No, I read it before the dream.
It was the preamble.

975
01:27:14,146 --> 01:27:17,815
It was about that book,
Flow My Tears, the Policeman said.

976
01:27:18,066 --> 01:27:23,279
- He won an award for that one.
- That's the one he wrote really fast.

977
01:27:23,488 --> 01:27:27,867
It just flowed out of him.
He felt he was channeling it.

978
01:27:28,076 --> 01:27:31,495
So four years later,
he was at this party.

979
01:27:31,705 --> 01:27:35,374
He met a woman with the same name
as the woman in the book.

980
01:27:35,667 --> 01:27:39,503
Her boyfriend had the same name
as the boyfriend in the book.

981
01:27:39,713 --> 01:27:42,965
She had an affair
with the chief of police.

982
01:27:43,175 --> 01:27:46,636
He had the same name
as the chief in his book.

983
01:27:46,887 --> 01:27:50,640
Everything she's saying
is right out of his book.

984
01:27:50,807 --> 01:27:54,435
That really freaks him out,
but what can he do?

985
01:27:54,645 --> 01:27:57,813
Shortly after that,
he was mailing a letter...

986
01:27:58,023 --> 01:28:03,319
...and he saw this kind of
shady-Iooking guy standing by his car.

987
01:28:03,528 --> 01:28:08,407
But instead of avoiding him,
he said, "Can I help you?"

988
01:28:08,659 --> 01:28:11,035
The guy said, "I ran out of gas."

989
01:28:11,286 --> 01:28:15,373
He hands him some money,
which he never would've done.

990
01:28:15,582 --> 01:28:17,333
He gets home and thinks:

991
01:28:17,542 --> 01:28:21,587
"This guy can't get to a gas station.
He's out of gas."

992
01:28:21,797 --> 01:28:27,134
So he goes back, finds the guy
and takes him to a gas station.

993
01:28:27,427 --> 01:28:31,347
As he pulls up he thinks,
"This is in my book too.

994
01:28:31,682 --> 01:28:35,267
This exact station. This exact guy.
Everything."

995
01:28:35,477 --> 01:28:38,771
So this whole episode
is kind of creepy, right?

996
01:28:39,022 --> 01:28:43,067
He's telling his priest
how he wrote this book...

997
01:28:43,276 --> 01:28:46,696
...and four years later
all these things happened.

998
01:28:46,905 --> 01:28:50,658
And the priest says,
"That's the Book of Acts."

999
01:28:50,867 --> 01:28:53,369
He's like, "I've never read it."

1000
01:28:53,620 --> 01:28:57,373
So he reads the Book of Acts,
and it's uncanny.

1001
01:28:57,624 --> 01:29:01,460
Even the characters' names
are the same as in the Bible.

1002
01:29:01,670 --> 01:29:05,339
The Book of Acts
takes place in 50 A.D.

1003
01:29:05,549 --> 01:29:09,552
So Dick had this theory
that time was an illusion...

1004
01:29:09,761 --> 01:29:11,887
...and that we were all in 50 A.D.

1005
01:29:12,097 --> 01:29:15,850
The reason he wrote this book
was that he somehow...

1006
01:29:16,059 --> 01:29:19,228
...punctured through
this veil of time.

1007
01:29:19,521 --> 01:29:23,607
He'd seen what was going on
in the Book of Acts.

1008
01:29:23,859 --> 01:29:28,279
He was really into Gnosticism
and the idea that this demon...

1009
01:29:28,488 --> 01:29:32,158
...created this illusion of time
to make us forget...

1010
01:29:32,451 --> 01:29:37,747
...that Christ was to return
and the kingdom of God would arrive.

1011
01:29:37,956 --> 01:29:42,585
Someone's trying to make us forget
that God is imminent.

1012
01:29:42,836 --> 01:29:45,212
That's what time and history is.

1013
01:29:45,422 --> 01:29:49,508
This kind of continuous
daydream or distraction.

1014
01:29:49,676 --> 01:29:54,430
I read it and thought, "That's weird."
And that night I had a dream.

1015
01:29:54,681 --> 01:29:58,017
There was this guy who
was supposed to be psychic.

1016
01:29:58,226 --> 01:30:01,228
But I was, like,
"He's not really a psychic."

1017
01:30:01,480 --> 01:30:06,358
Then suddenly I start floating,
levitating up to the ceiling.

1018
01:30:06,777 --> 01:30:11,906
As I almost go through the roof,
I'm like, "Okay, I believe you."

1019
01:30:12,115 --> 01:30:15,868
And I float down,
and as my feet touch the ground...

1020
01:30:16,119 --> 01:30:20,706
...the psychic turns into a woman
in a green dress, Lady Gregory.

1021
01:30:20,916 --> 01:30:24,335
Lady Gregory was Yeats' patron,
this Irish person.

1022
01:30:24,586 --> 01:30:26,962
Though I'd never seen her image...

1023
01:30:27,172 --> 01:30:31,467
...I was sure that this was
the face of Lady Gregory.

1024
01:30:31,718 --> 01:30:34,095
So Lady Gregory turns to me and says:

1025
01:30:34,346 --> 01:30:37,556
"Let me explain
the nature of the universe.

1026
01:30:37,766 --> 01:30:41,811
Philip K. Dick is right about time,
but wrong that it's 50 A.D.

1027
01:30:42,062 --> 01:30:47,024
Actually, there's only one instant,
right now. And it's eternity.

1028
01:30:47,234 --> 01:30:52,363
It's an instant in which God
is posing a question, which is:

1029
01:30:52,614 --> 01:30:57,743
'Do you wanna be one with eternity,
do you wanna be in heaven? '

1030
01:30:57,994 --> 01:31:01,914
And we're all saying,
'No, thank you. Not just yet."'

1031
01:31:02,165 --> 01:31:06,710
So time is just this constant
saying no to God's invitation.

1032
01:31:06,920 --> 01:31:11,257
That's what time is.
It's no more 50 A.D. Than it's 2001.

1033
01:31:11,466 --> 01:31:15,553
There's just one instant,
and that's what we're always in.

1034
01:31:15,887 --> 01:31:20,683
Then she tells me that this is
the narrative of everyone's life.

1035
01:31:20,892 --> 01:31:24,937
Behind the huge difference,
there is but one story...

1036
01:31:25,147 --> 01:31:27,606
...of moving from the no
to the yes.

1037
01:31:27,858 --> 01:31:30,901
All of life is,
"No, thank you. No, thank you."

1038
01:31:31,111 --> 01:31:33,779
Then ultimately it's, "Yes, I give in.

1039
01:31:34,030 --> 01:31:38,367
Yes, I accept. Yes, I embrace."
That's the journey.

1040
01:31:38,618 --> 01:31:42,454
Everyone gets to the yes
in the end, right?

1041
01:31:42,664 --> 01:31:43,664
Right.

1042
01:31:43,874 --> 01:31:47,626
So we continue walking,
and my dog runs over to me.

1043
01:31:47,878 --> 01:31:50,629
I'm so happy.
He's been dead for years.

1044
01:31:50,839 --> 01:31:54,592
So I'm petting him,
and there's this gross stuff...

1045
01:31:54,801 --> 01:31:57,094
...coming out of his stomach.

1046
01:31:57,345 --> 01:32:00,431
I look over at Lady Gregory,
and she coughs.

1047
01:32:00,640 --> 01:32:02,725
She's like, "Excuse me."

1048
01:32:02,934 --> 01:32:07,313
And vomit dribbles down her chin.
It smells really bad.

1049
01:32:07,606 --> 01:32:12,401
And I think,
"That's not just the smell of vomit.

1050
01:32:12,652 --> 01:32:17,698
That's the smell of dead-person vomit."
So it's, like, doubly foul.

1051
01:32:17,949 --> 01:32:23,329
I realize I'm in the land of the dead.
Everyone around me was dead.

1052
01:32:23,538 --> 01:32:27,458
My dog had been dead 10 years,
Lady Gregory a lot longer.

1053
01:32:27,667 --> 01:32:31,503
When I woke up, I was like,
"That wasn't a dream.

1054
01:32:31,713 --> 01:32:35,925
That was a visitation
to this place, the land of the dead."

1055
01:32:36,134 --> 01:32:38,594
So how did you finally get out of it?

1056
01:32:38,887 --> 01:32:43,015
It was, like, one of those
life-altering experiences.

1057
01:32:43,225 --> 01:32:46,352
I never looked at the world
the same way again.

1058
01:32:46,561 --> 01:32:49,772
But how did you finally
get out of the dream?

1059
01:32:49,981 --> 01:32:52,650
That's my problem. I'm trapped.

1060
01:32:52,859 --> 01:32:57,738
I keep thinking I'm waking up,
but I'm still in a dream.

1061
01:32:57,948 --> 01:33:02,159
I wanna wake up for real.
How do you really wake up?

1062
01:33:02,369 --> 01:33:06,038
I don't know.
I'm not very good at that anymore.

1063
01:33:06,289 --> 01:33:11,335
But if that's what you're thinking,
you should, if you can.

1064
01:33:11,544 --> 01:33:14,463
Because someday, you won't be able to.

1065
01:33:14,673 --> 01:33:17,716
But it's easy. You know, just wake up.

